    <edge source="1. The Colonization Board's proposal to Suzanne Carstens is an attempt to address two issues:" target="1. The story suggests that a change in societal values and attitudes towards unmarried women has led to the enactment of stricter laws and regulations, which criminalize actions that were previously not considered crimes. This is explained by MacDonald, who notes that in the past, unmarried women often became &quot;old maids&quot; who were dedicated to improving the morals and behavior of society. However, with fewer men available for marriage, more women are competing for husbands, leading to an increase in certain types of crimes such as shoplifting, badger games, poisonings, and petty crimes. As a result, there are now more puritanical societies and silly little laws on the books, which can lead to people being thrown in jail for things like violating a woman's privacy.&#10;2. The idea of getting women to colonize is presented as a solution to this issue because it would address the underlying imbalance between men and women on Earth. By encouraging more women to emigrate to colony planets, the Colonization Board hopes to reduce competition for men and decrease the number of crimes related to husband-hunting. This would also help increase the number of male applicants for emigration, as fewer men would be deterred by the prospect of living on a planet where women outnumber men five to three.&#10;3. However, it is important to note that this solution may not be without its own challenges and ethical concerns. As mentioned in the story, efforts to legalize polygamy or disregard moral codes in order to encourage colonization could have unintended consequences and raise questions about the treatment of individuals and society as a whole. It would be crucial to consider these factors carefully when developing solutions to this issue.">
